arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VI: Late Nabataean pre CE 106 minor collapses and repairs. Probable early collapse of the Baroque Room and damage occurs in both the Anteroom and Shrine Room. The tabun in Room A is used to store CE 1st c. Nabataean fine wares. East 'Cistern" used as a dump. Bath Complex built.

Locus 70 is the oblique vertical channel cut into the west face of the West Precinct Wall near the entrance to the “bathroom.” The channel is slanted from south to north at an approximate angle of 60 degrees. The channel is cut directly into the ashlars of the wall, with chisel marks still visible. There is no clear terminus of the channel, and its top disappears into the degraded sandstone ashlars that have worn away any trace of the channel. Most likely, this channel, like the other channels in the “entrance room,” was part of the water circulation system of the bath complex. The excavators phase this locus to the main construction period of the bath complex, seeing it as an addition to the West Precinct Wall for the specific needs of the bath complex and its water requirements.
0.13 m north south -by- 0.13 m east west.
